      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The \"stolen goods\" analogy is just a quick way to picture the statistical risk! In the mathematical sense, that \"noise\" is the inherent randomness—the sampling variability—that exists in any finite sample of data. It's the statistical equivalent of the random shuffling of a deck of cards; even if the deck is perfectly ordered (the null hypothesis is true), the way you draw the cards is random.\n\nThe 0.05 cutoff is a convention, a historical agreement, often rooted in the idea of controlling the Type I error rate—the risk of falsely concluding there *is* an effect when there truly isn't one. So, when you say the \"noise\" feels like something more, you are intuitively grasping the difference between *statistical significance* (the p-value) and *practical significance* (the effect size).\n\nThink of it this way: the 0.05 line is the agreed-upon tolerance for being wrong about the null hypothesis. If your p-value is 0.06, you are admitting, \"I'm 6% sure this isn't just a random fluke, but I haven't crossed the established line of certainty.\" It's a",
      "source": "target",
